{"id":"project-LICHEN-nee4","title":"scheduler.rs: weak PRNG produces identical jitter for calls in same millisecond","description":"File: rust/lichen-node/src/scheduler.rs:365-384

The random_range function uses a time-seeded LCG that produces identical output for calls within the same millisecond:

```rust
fn random_range(min: u64, max: u64) -> u64 {
    let seed = SystemTime::now()
        .duration_since(UNIX_EPOCH)
        .unwrap_or(Duration::from_secs(0))
        .as_nanos() as u64;
    let a: u64 = 1664525;
    let c: u64 = 1013904223;
    let m: u64 = 1 << 32;
    let random = (seed.wrapping_mul(a).wrapping_add(c)) % m;
    min + (random % (max - min + 1))
}
```

Problems:
1. No state between calls - same millisecond = same output
2. If multiple nodes power on simultaneously, they get identical jitter
3. This defeats the thundering herd prevention that jitter is supposed to provide

Fix: Maintain PRNG state between calls, or add a per-node salt (e.g., from IID).","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"me@mark.atwood.name","created_at":"2026-07-12T06:35:10.983861Z","created_by":"Mark Atwood","updated_at":"2026-07-12T06:35:10.983895Z"}

